VRefreshing recitals
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe first evening of the two-day music fete featuring young artistes, organised by Visakha Music Academy, continued with a recital on veena by duo Smrithi A. Chitra and Apoorva Priyanka (disciples of reputed vainika Ramavarapu Madhuri Devi). It marked an exciting finale of the evening. The items they mainly played with ragam, neravu and swaram wereKanjadalayatakshi(Kambhoji),Chintayamyaham(Bhairavi) andAmmaraavamma(Kalyani). Exhibiting erudition and admirable ambidexterity even while negotiating break-neck speed, they kept all delighted. V.S.J. Sarma on mridangam lent invigorating support.The second evening featured a vocal recital, first by N. AdityaViswanath with Ch. Rama Kiranmayi on violin and V. Sai Srikar on mridangam. The deeply bass timbre of his voice contributed colour to his exposition. He mainly sangBajanaseyave(Kalyani) andKailaasanadhena(Kambhoji). Soulful concern for purity of note and its quality and quantity wise attribution in the musical scale she chose to sing marked the vocal recital rendered next by K. Nikhitha Srivalli. Prime disciple of Akashvani vocalist M. Jalajakshi, she realised her ambition singing serenely in a leisurely tempo. Thus evolving refreshing melody all along, she delightfully took the audience into trance. The highlights were elaboration ofBalakanakamaya chela(Athana),Hiranmayeem(Lalitha) with aalapana and swaram andNijadasavarada(Kalyani) additionally with invigorating neravu. M.P.S. Ravali on violin and M.V. Mehar Kalyani on mridangam adorably sustained the tranquil tenor and tempo.
